{"key":"processedPost-9114856","value":{"id":9114856,"first":9113919,"last":9114856,"when":1224693797,"utime":"10/22/08 07:43 PM","content":"I've refrigerated my indoor oyster and shiitake greenhouses for many years.&nbsp; Simply get one of those stand-alone air conditioners from a hardware store and some insulated, flexible ducting.<br />You run flex duct from the evaporator output(cold air) to the top of your greenhouse.&nbsp; This is the cold air supply, and by ducting it into the top, the cold air sinks to the bottom, where you duct your return air to the air intake side of the portable AC unit.<br />A third 4\" clothes dryer hose routes the output of the condenser coil, which blows hot air, to the outside of your house.<br />Be careful though.&nbsp; If your mushrooms sporulate and you don't harvest them in time, this picture below shows the mess from a flush of oyster mushrooms that you'll have to clean up from the evaporator coil of the AC.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/06-52/743652096-mini-greenhouse_AC_with_Oyster_spores_005a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/06-52/743652096-thumb_mini-greenhouse_AC_with_Oyster_spores_005a.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: Turning a Greenhouse Into a refrigerator???"}}